<h2>Ubuntu Tutorial</h2>
<h3><strong>Step 1 - </strong> Virtual Box & Ubuntu 14.04</h3>
<section>
{{#if emberTutorial.checkValue_1}}
<p></p>
{{else}}
<p>Everything has a beginning, and for this tutorial is having Ubuntu ready to go. 
Although you could do the same on OSX and Windows, the steps are simply too different
 for me to account for in this guide.</p>
<p>If you are using Ubuntu 14.04 already, then awesome as you can mark the section as
 complete and head to the overall dependencies. If not, stick around to a quick how to: </p>
<p>1. Get <a href="https://www.virtualbox.org/wiki/Downloads" target="_blank">VirtualBox</a> and install it on your operating system.
If you do not know what it is, VirtualBox is a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Virtualization" target="_blank">virtualization</a>  
program that allows you to run almost any OS inside your current one (not to be confused with
<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Operating-system-level_virtualization" target="_blank">containers</a> like
<a href="https://www.docker.com/" target="_blank">Docker</a> which are related, but not the same.)</p>
<p>2. Download <a href="http://releases.ubuntu.com/14.04/" target="_blank">Ubuntu 14.04.4 LTS</a> Desktop ISO image.
 If you know that you are using a x64 bit system, get the amd64 .iso, otherwise just grab the i386 .iso</p>
<p>3. Open VirtualBox and create a new Ubuntu machine matching x64 for amd64 image or x32 for i386 image. 
Have at least 1GB for RAM, and create a new VDI (virtualBox image) that contains at least 15 GB of Hard Drive (20GB is better.) 
I recommend having it to be a fixed size due to performance, but it is your call!</p>
<p>4. Open the settings for your newly created machine and add the image as a new optical disk.</p>
<p>5. Start the machine and go through the installation process. Make sure to select the erase disk 
option for a quick and painless install (which only handles the created virtual disk, so don't worry.)</p>
<p>6. Upon login, Go to the VirtualBox menu and click Devices followed by "Insert Guest Additions CS image". Run the software, install it and then restart the virtual machine.</p>
<p>7. Maximize the VirtualBox window, and check to see if the screen covers the entire window like below:</p>
<p><a href="http://imgur.com/NyqsCXa" target="_blank"><img height=300px src="http://i.imgur.com/NyqsCXa.png" title="source: imgur.com" /></a></p>
<p>If not, search for possible troubleshoots on Google (or Bing if that's your thing because it is mine due to the reward points.)</p>
{{/if}}
